\begin_layout Title
Random vs.
 non-Random Grammar
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Linas Vepstas
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This presents a hypothesis, based on a discovery in my data, about how to
 tell apart random grammar from actual English grammar.
 A certain fairly simple distribution has a knee int's graph, located at
 
\begin_inset Formula $N=400$
\end_inset

 word observations.
 That is, the distribution behaves differently when a word is observed less
 than 400 times in this dataset, vs.
 being observed more than that many times.
 I make the hypothesis that this is the point where we can distinguish 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 English grammar, vs.
 the grammar of random text.
 The hypothsis is supported by the post-facto observation that the input
 corpus has a lot of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

junk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in it: tables of contents, chapter headings, indexes, assorted quotes in
 latin and other foreign languages, and so on.
 This 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

junk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 has an essentially random or arbitrary grammar to it.
 Of course, the tools will compute word-pair mutual information for for
 this junk, and the MST parser will happily parse it, using this inflated
 MI, and report it as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 I believe that the knee in the distribution graph distinguishes what can
 be taken as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random grammar
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, from actual English grammar.
 
\end_layout

