What does this mean? What is this saying? Here's what I think it is saying:
 when a word is observed less than about 400 times, the way it participates
 in the grammar is as if it were a part of a radnom network, with a scaling
 factor of 3/2 primarily determined by the statistics of random planar trees.
 That is, when a word is observed only a few times, the MI score is necessarily
 going to be high, since it is very strongly assocaited with the context
 that its in.
 A small number of contexts means that anything that occurs in those contexts
 will have a high MI.
 When parsing setneces with these 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rare
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 words, the MST parse will award them, will preferentially choose them for
 the parse because of thier high MI.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Put it this way: the MST parser does not know if we are feeding it English,
 or random garbled strings of junk.
 It will happily collect word-pairs and assign high MI values to rare word-pairs
, even if its random junk.
 The resulting distribution of disjuncts is essentially the distribution
 of disjuncts formed on planar parse trees of random sentences.
 That is my hypothesis for the 
\begin_inset Formula $N<400$
\end_inset

 data.
 Its a testable hypothesis.
 I have not (yet) tested it.
\end_layout

